<h4 class="index-section-header">Early 2026</h4>
<div class="index-intro-section">
<p>
  The new year of 2026 sees a large update to the <a href="/">Intertwined milestones of the PC industry and the Scene</a>. 
  There are both new articles and several rewrites for entries for the late 1970s and 1980s; 
  The first copy protections, 
  Widespread disk copying leads to copy protections, 
  The first groups, 
  The earliest cracktros, 
  Commercial Disk Copy Protections, 
  The year of the Commodore 64, 
  The Berlin Bear controversy, and more!
</p>
</div>
<h4 class="index-section-header">Late 2025</h4>
<div class="index-intro-section">
<p>
  The last half of the year has seen the introduction of a much-desired ANSI to HTML conversion sitewide. 
  All the glorious BBS ads from the 1980s and 1990s are now properly displayed as text!
</p>
<p>
  Following this, there has been a major upload of the many ANSI and binary text artworks created by the prolific artgroups of the 1990s, 
  <a href="/g/insane-creators-enterprise">iCE Advertisements</a> and <a href="/g/acid-productions">ACiD Productions</a>. 
  They're now the <a href="/releaser">top two groups</a>  for total number of artifacts on the site.
</p>
<p>
Also, the plain text reader has been updated to use a number of legacy fonts depending on the artifact. 
Fonts include the IBM MDA for PC texts from the 1980s, an IBM CGA font for ANSI <a href="/f/ba2bcbb">art</a> for the same period. 
And the Amiga texts now have a more appropriate <a href="/f/ab1daf8">dark grey background</a>, 
while <a href="/f/b82d002">Amiga ANSI</a> can be viewed using the MicroKnight styled font.
</p>
</div>
<h4 class="index-section-header">Mid 2025</h4>
<div class="index-intro-section">
<p>
  The mid-year sees another discovery of an extensive Scene releases backup, but captured from the late 90s. 
  And that has helped us <a href="/files/new-uploads">improve</a> the collection on our site.
</p>
<p>
So far, using these compact disc backups, we have been able to flesh out the major game groups of 1996, 
including the replacement of incomplete or broken text files. A common problem for releases that were butchered by third parties and shared online. 
However, until now, without these nearly 30-year-old original release archives, we were unable to verify or fix these problematic artifacts.
</p>
<p>
  Targeted top-tier game groups include, 
  <a href="/g/hybrid">Hybrid</a>, <a href="/g/prestige">Prestige</a>, 
  <a href="/g/paradigm">Paradigm</a>, <a href="/g/class">Class</a>,
  <a href="/g/razor-1911">Razor 1911</a> and a collection of FTP site ads. You can follow along using the <a href="/files/new-uploads">new uploads link</a>.
</p>
<p>
Also, a new <a href="/brokentexts">Broken text files</a> FAQ page has been added to the site. 
In it, we explain about the corrupt and incorrect texts and NFO files on the site. Why they exist and how they came about.
</p>
</div>
<h4 class="index-section-header">Early 2025</h4>
<div class="index-intro-section">
<p>
    The new year has continued to see new additions to the website.
    With the continued inclusion of scene files backed up on the HMS Bounty BBS tapes has been a significant focus, 
    and we are now up to the year of 1994. And these releases will probably continue on for a few more years.<br>
    These new discoveries has also meant some of the milestones listed on the <a href="/">home welcome</a> page have been revised
    and the page now also offers direct links to the highlights, such as <em><a href="/#:~:text=The%20first%20group">The first group</a></em>.
</p>
<p>
    There is a new <a href="/areacodes">BBS area codes page</a> for North America with a complete list of districts, as well as search and lookup features.
</p>
<p>
    On the backend, the site has expanded its support for more archive and compression types for hosted artifacts, including: 
    <code>.cab</code>, <code>.zst</code>, <code>.xz</code>, <code>.arj</code>, <code>.arc</code>, <code>.7z</code>.
</p>
</div>
<h4 class="index-section-header">Late 2024</h4>
<div class="index-intro-section">
<p>
    In the second half of 2024, we added thousands of new artifacts of historical importance to the scene to the website. 
    These include many new <a href="/files/how-to">Unprotect textfiles</a>, a couple intros [<a href="/f/ab22918">1</a>, 
    <a href="/f/ad27738">2</a>] from the early to late 1980s, 
    and <a href="/files/oldest">Scene releases</a> such as NFOs, trainers, and intros from 1988 to the early 1990s.
</p><p>
    The unprotected texts were anonymously submitted, thank you!
</p><p>
    The 1988+ files came from the dump of "<a href="/g/hms-bounty-bbs">The HMS Bounty</a>" BBS backup tapes, 
    which an individual* discovered in storage and painfully digitalized and assembled for online preservation.
    <br>* A massive thank you to you!
</p>
</div>
